# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arrack
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arrack/1925-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] A referendum was held on 4 April 1925 in the Australian state of Western Australia on the topic of prohibition.
[src:arrack/1925-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] The Licensing Act Amendment Act 1922 (No.39 of 1922) was assented to by the Governor of Western Australia on 22 December 1922.
[src:arrack/1925-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] Section 60 of the Act (which became Section 87(e) of the Licensing Act 1911) stipulated that "in 1925, and in every fifth year thereafter... there shall be taken a poll of the electors in every electoral district on the proposal that prohibition shall come into force in Western Australia".
[src:arrack/1925-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] It also provided that if prohibition was passed, then in subsequent polls "the proposal shall be that licenses for the sale of intoxicating liquor shall be restored".
[src:arrack/1925-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] The franchise was to be the same as that for the Western Australian Legislative Assembly, and a proposal could only be carried if 60% of all votes were in favour.
[src:arrack/1925-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] Prior to the enactment of this provision, two referendums, one in 1911 and another in 1921, had rejected prohibition.
[src:arrack/1925-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] Despite the legislation calling for five-yearly referendums, only one more was held in 1950.
[src:arrack/1925-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] Section 87 of the Licensing Act was repealed in 1959.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] A referendum concerning introducing prohibition in New South Wales was put to voters on 1 September 1928.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] Six o'clock closing was introduced during the First World War, partly as an attempt to improve public morality and partly as a war austerity measure.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] Before this reform, most hotels and public houses in Australia closed their bars at 11 or 11:30 pm.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] Support for changing hotel closing times originally came from the temperance movement, which hoped that implementing restrictions on the sale of alcohol would lead eventually to its total prohibition.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] Although the movement had been active since the 1870s, it had been gaining ground since the 1900s following the introduction of 6 o'clock retail trade closing, first legislated in Western Australia in 1897.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] The argument made by the temperance movement challenged the grounds for public houses being "kept open while bakers' shops were shut".
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] Prominent groups in this movement were the Woman's Christian Temperance Union and the Rechabites.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] The first state to introduce early closing was South Australia in March 1916 where the rationale was to reduce drunkenness, and followed a widely subscribed petition.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] The Council of Churches urged such a measure in support of the war effort, but premier Peake, a teetotal Presbyterian, refused.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] Such a law was approved in a referendum held in conjunction with the 1915 state election.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] Six o'clock closing was subsequently adopted in New South Wales, Victoria, and Tasmania in the same year.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] It was introduced in New Zealand in December 1917.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] Western Australia adopted a 9 pm closing time, but Queensland retained the old closing times until it introduced 8 o'clock closing in 1923.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] The question of closing hours was put to New South Wales voters in a referendum held on 10 June 1916.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] The question had previously been put to the vote in December 1913 when the results of the *Local Option Poll* were in favour of 11 o'clock closing.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] The 1916 vote was influenced by a recent riot involving drunken soldiers.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] In February 1916, troops mutinied against conditions at the Casula Camp.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] They raided hotels in Liverpool before travelling by train to Sydney, where one soldier was shot dead in a riot at Central Railway station.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] Although 6 o'clock closing was introduced as a temporary measure, the government brought in extensions and discussed putting the matter to a referendum.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] In 1923, however, without testing the matter by a popular vote, the Fuller Nationalist government enacted 6 pm as the closing time.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] The question to be voted on was whether "prohibition, with compensation, shall come into force throughout New South Wales".
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] The referendum overwhelmingly rejected the introduction of prohibition.
[src:arrack/1928-new-south-wales-prohibition-referendum] This was the second of 5 referendums concerning the sale of alcohol in New South Wales, 3 of which dealt with the closing hour for licensed premises and clubs while the fifth concerned Sunday trading.
[src:arrack/1950-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] A referendum was held on 9 December 1950 in the Australian state of Western Australia on the topic of prohibition.
[src:arrack/1950-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] It was the state's fourth referendum on the topic of liquor licensing, and the second put to voters with the same wording.
[src:arrack/1950-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] The proposal to prohibit alcohol was rejected by 73% of voters.
[src:arrack/1950-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] The referendum was conducted pursuant to the Licensing Act 1911, specifically Section 87(e) which had been added by an amending act in 1922, and which mandated a referendum on the topic of liquor licensing every five years.
[src:arrack/1950-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] However, none had been conducted since the one in 1925.
[src:arrack/1950-western-australian-prohibition-referendum] No further polls were held on the topic of liquor licensing, and Section 87 of the Licensing Act was repealed in 1959.
[src:arrack/aam-panna] Unripe mango is a rich source of pectin, which gradually diminishes after the formation of the stone.
[src:arrack/aam-panna] Unripe mango is sour in taste because of the presence of oxalic, citric and malic acids.
[src:arrack/aam-panna] Aam panna or Aam Jhora, which is prepared using raw mangoes, cumin, and an assortment of other spices, quenches thirst and prevents the excessive loss of sodium chloride and iron during summer due to excessive sweating.
[src:arrack/aam-panna] The drink is mainly consumed in north India and Pakistan is considered beneficial in the treatment of gastrointestinal disorders.
[src:arrack/aam-panna] It is also a good source of vitamin B1 and B2, niacin, and vitamin C.
[src:arrack/aam-panna] In Indian and Pakistani culture, it is regarded as a tonic believed to increase resistance against tuberculosis, anemia, cholera and dysentery.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:arrack/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:arrack/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:arrack/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:arrack/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:arrack/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:arrack/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:arrack/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:arrack/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:arrack/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:arrack/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:arrack/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:arrack/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:arrack/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:arrack/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:arrack/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:arrack/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:arrack/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:arrack/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:arrack/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:arrack/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:arrack/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:arrack/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:arrack/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:arrack/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:arrack/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:arrack/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:arrack/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:arrack/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:arrack/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:arrack/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:arrack/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:arrack/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:arrack/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:arrack/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:arrack/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:arrack/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:arrack/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:arrack/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:arrack/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:arrack/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:arrack/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:arrack/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:arrack/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:arrack/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:arrack/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:arrack/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:arrack/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:arrack/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:arrack/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:arrack/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:arrack/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:arrack/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:arrack/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:arrack/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:arrack/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:arrack/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:arrack/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:arrack/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:arrack/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:arrack/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:arrack/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:arrack/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:arrack/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:arrack/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:arrack/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:arrack/acerum] In the 1970s, distillers began to produce alcohol from maple syrup.
[src:arrack/acerum] Although some distilled alcohol tests were then carried out in university laboratories, it was not until the 1990s that certain maple syrup producers began to produce a wine based on this sweet resource, which was initially called Acer.
[src:arrack/acerum] One of the first producers of Acerum was The Domaine Acer, based in Témiscouata, Quebec.
[src:arrack/acerum] When Vallier Robert took the reins of his family maple business in 1990, he quickly saw the potential to make alcohol.
[src:arrack/acerum] In 1996, the maple farmer was granted the first licence to produce artisanal maple-based alcoholic beverages.
[src:arrack/acerum] He began creating several varieties of maple sap wine, including dry, sparkling and dessert wines.
[src:arrack/acerum] During the same period, some distilleries began to market maple eau-de-vie, but it was not until December 2017 that the name Acerum appeared for the first time for a maple eau-de-vie.
[src:arrack/acerum] As defined by the specifications of the UDSÉ, Acerum must be entirely manufactured in the province of Quebec, in Canada, with maple syrup, maple concentrate, or maple sap from Quebec maples.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Classic signs of addiction include compulsive engagement in rewarding stimuli, preoccupation with substances or behavior, and continued use despite negative consequences.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Habits and patterns associated with addiction are typically characterized by immediate gratification (short-term reward), coupled with delayed deleterious effects (long-term costs).
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Examples of substance addiction include alcoholism, cannabis addiction, amphetamine addiction, cocaine addiction, nicotine addiction, opioid addiction, and eating or food addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Behavioral addictions may include gambling addiction, shopping addiction, pornography addiction, internet addiction, video game addiction, and sexual addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The DSM-5 and ICD-10 only recognize gambling addictions as behavioral addictions, but the ICD-11 also recognizes gaming addictions.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Signs and symptoms of drug addiction can vary depending on the type of addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] SUD belongs to the class of substance-related disorders, is a chronic and relapsing brain disorder that features drug seeking and drug abuse, despite their harmful effects.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] This form of addiction changes brain circuitry such that the brain's reward system is compromised, causing functional consequences for stress management and self-control.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Damage to the functions of the organs involved can persist throughout a lifetime and cause death if untreated.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Substances involved with drug addiction include alcohol, nicotine, marijuana, opioids, cocaine, amphetamines, and even foods with high fat and sugar content.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Addictions can begin experimentally in social contexts and can arise from the use of prescribed medications or a variety of other measures.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] It has been shown to work in phenomenological, conditioning (operant and classical), cognitive models, and the cue reactivity model.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] However, no one model completely illustrates substance abuse.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The diagnostic criteria for food or eating addiction has not been categorized or defined in references such as the *Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders* (DSM) and is based on subjective experiences similar to substance use disorders.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Food addiction may be found in those with eating disorders, though not all people with eating disorders have food addiction and not all of those with food addiction have a diagnosed eating disorder.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Long-term frequent and excessive consumption of foods high in fat, salt, or sugar, such as chocolate, can produce an addiction similar to drugs since they trigger the brain's reward system, such that the individual may desire the same foods to an increasing degree over time.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The signals sent when consuming highly palatable foods have the ability to counteract the body's signals for fullness and persistent cravings will result.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Those who show signs of food addiction may develop food tolerances, in which they eat more, despite the food becoming less satisfactory.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Chocolate's sweet flavor and pharmacological ingredients are known to create a strong craving or feel 'addictive' to consumers.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] A person who has a strong liking for chocolate may refer to themselves as a chocoholic.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Risk factors for developing food addiction include excessive overeating and impulsivity.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The Yale Food Addiction Scale (YFAS), version 2.0, is the current standard measure for assessing whether an individual exhibits signs and symptoms of food addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] It was developed in 2009 at Yale University on the hypothesis that foods high in fat, sugar, and salt have addictive-like effects which contribute to problematic eating habits.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The YFAS is designed to address 11 substance-related and addictive disorders (SRADs) using a 25-item self-report questionnaire, based on the diagnostic criteria for SRADs as per the DSM-5.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] A potential food addiction diagnosis is predicted by the presence of at least two out of 11 SRADs and a significant impairment to daily activities.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The Barratt Impulsiveness Scale, specifically the BIS-11 scale, and the UPPS-P Impulsive Behavior subscales of Negative Urgency and Lack of Perseverance have been shown to have a relation to food addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The term *behavioral addiction* refers to a compulsion to engage in a natural reward – which is an inherently rewarding behavior (i.e., desirable or appealing) – despite adverse consequences.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Preclinical evidence has demonstrated that marked increases in the expression of ΔFosB through repetitive and excessive exposure to a natural reward induces the same behavioral effects and neuroplasticity as occurs in a drug addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Addiction can exist without psychotropic drugs, an idea that was popularized by psychologist Stanton Peele.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Such addictions may be passive or active, but they commonly contain reinforcing features, which are found in most addictions.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Sexual behavior, eating, gambling, playing video games, and shopping are all associated with compulsive behaviors in humans and have been shown to activate the mesolimbic pathway and other parts of the reward system.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Based on this evidence, sexual addiction, gambling addiction, video game addiction, and shopping addiction are classified accordingly.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Personality theories of addiction are psychological models that associate personality traits or modes of thinking (i.e., affective states) with an individual's proclivity for developing an addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Data analysis demonstrates that psychological profiles of drug users and non-users have significant differences, and the psychological predisposition to using different drugs may be different.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The transtheoretical model of change (TTM) can point to how someone may be conceptualizing their addiction and the thoughts around it, including not being aware of their addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Cognitive control and stimulus control, which is associated with operant and classical conditioning, represent opposite processes (i.e., internal vs external or environmental, respectively) that compete over the control of an individual's elicited behaviors.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Cognitive control, and particularly inhibitory control over behavior, is impaired in both addiction and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Stimulus-driven behavioral responses (i.e., stimulus control) that are associated with a particular rewarding stimulus tend to dominate one's behavior in an addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] In operant conditioning, behavior is influenced by outside stimuli, such as a drug.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Stimulus control is using the absence of the stimulus or the presence of a reward to influence the resulting behavior.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Cognitive control is the intentional selection of thoughts, behaviors, and emotions based on our environment.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] It has been shown that drugs alter the way our brains function and their structure.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Cognitive functions such as learning, memory, and impulse control, are affected by drugs.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] These effects promote drug use, as well as hinder the ability to abstain from it.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The increase in dopamine release is prominent in drug use, specifically in the ventral striatum and the nucleus accumbens.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Dopamine is responsible for producing pleasurable feelings, as well as driving us to perform important life activities.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Addictive drugs cause a significant increase in this reward system, causing a large increase in dopamine signaling as well as increase in reward-seeking behavior, in turn motivating drug use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] This promotes the development of a maladaptive drug to stimulus relationship.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Early drug use leads to these maladaptive associations, later affecting cognitive processes used for coping, which are needed to abstain from them successfully.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Some scholars have proposed evolutionary explanations for addiction, suggesting that vulnerabilities to substance or behavioural dependence reflect by-products or dysregulated expressions of reward and learning systems that were adaptive in ancestral environments.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Classic accounts argue that purified drugs and rapid delivery methods exploit ancient motivational circuitry by providing "false fitness signals" that mimic cues once linked to survival or reproduction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Other reviews emphasise how psychoactive substances and behavioural reinforcers act on conserved mechanisms for reward, reinforcement, and emotion, which in modern settings can be overstimulated or maladapted.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] These perspectives do not replace proximate neurobiological models, but aim instead to situate contemporary patterns of vulnerability within a broader evolutionary framework.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Several genetic and environmental risk factors exist for developing an addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Genetic and environmental risk factors each account for roughly half of an individual's risk for developing an addiction; the contribution from epigenetic risk factors to the total risk is unknown.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Even in individuals with a relatively low genetic risk, exposure to sufficiently high doses of an addictive drug for a long period of time (e.g., weeks–months) can result in an addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Adverse childhood events are associated with negative health outcomes, such as substance use disorder.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Childhood abuse or exposure to violent crime is related to developing a mood or anxiety disorder, as well as a risk of substance dependence.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Genetic factors, along with socio-environmental (e.g., psychosocial) factors, have been established as significant contributors to addiction vulnerability.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Genetic factors account for 40–60% of the risk factors for alcoholism.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Similar rates of heritability for other types of drug addiction have been indicated, specifically in genes that encode the Alpha5 Nicotinic Acetylcholine Receptor.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Knestler hypothesized in 1964 that a gene or group of genes might contribute to predisposition to addiction in several ways.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] For example, altered levels of a normal protein due to environmental factors may change the structure or functioning of specific brain neurons during development.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] These altered brain neurons could affect the susceptibility of an individual to an initial drug use experience.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] In support of this hypothesis, animal studies have shown that environmental factors such as stress can affect an animal's genetic expression.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] In humans, twin studies into addiction have provided some of the highest-quality evidence of this link, with results finding that if one twin is affected by addiction, the other twin is likely to be as well, and to the same substance.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The data implicating specific genes in the development of drug addiction is mixed for most genes.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Many addiction studies that aim to identify specific genes focus on common variants with allele frequencies of greater than 5% in the general population.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Genome-wide association studies (GWAS) are used to examine genetic associations with dependence, addiction, and drug use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] These studies rarely identify genes from proteins previously described via animal knockout models and candidate gene analysis.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Instead, large percentages of genes involved in processes such as cell adhesion are commonly identified.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The important effects of endophenotypes are typically not capable of being captured by these methods.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Genes identified in GWAS for drug addiction may be involved either in adjusting brain behavior before drug experiences, subsequent to them, or both.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Stress can play a central and key role in the development and persistence of addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] It can influence neurophysiological pathways, decision-making processes, and relapse risk.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Acute and chronic stress can activate the hypothalamic pituitary adrenal gland, which can result in elevated cortisol and corticotropin-releasing factor.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] These hormonal changes alter reward processing and increase the motivational value of substances, mainly those that temporarily reduce negative affect.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] In preclinical models, repeated stress exposure aids dopamine release in the nucleus accumbens and sensitizes the mesolimbic reward system, increasing the reinforcing aspects of drugs.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Chronic stress also disturbs glutamatergic signaling in the pre frontal cortex, which impairs executive functions including inhibitory control and self regulation.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] These changes increase the susceptibility to compulsive drug seeking and decrease the ability to ignore conditioned cues that are associated with substance use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Stress can also be one of the most reliable predictors of a potential relapse.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Human neuroimaging studies show that stress induced activation of the amygdala and reduced pre frontal cortex regulation correlate with self reported craving and subsequent return to use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Individuals that have a history of trauma or chronic social stress (things like discrimination, poverty, or unstable housing) show an increased risk for substance use disorders due to both neurobiological sensitization and behavioral coping responses.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Stress interacts very strongly with reward circuitry and decision-making systems; this means many treatment approaches integrate stress-reduction strategies.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] These include cognitive behavioral therapy, mindfulness-based interventions, and medications targeting stress-related neurochemistry.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Environmental risk factors for addiction are the experiences of an individual during their lifetime that interact with the individual's genetic composition to increase or decrease his or her vulnerability to addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] For example, after the nationwide outbreak of COVID-19 in China, more people quit (vs. started) smoking.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] People who smoke, on average, reduced the quantity of cigarettes they consumed.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] More generally, several different environmental factors have been implicated as risk factors for addiction, including various psychosocial stressors.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The National Institute on Drug Abuse (NIDA) and studies cite lack of parental supervision, the prevalence of peer substance use, substance availability, and poverty as risk factors for substance use among children and adolescents.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The brain disease model of addiction posits that an individual's exposure to an addictive drug is the most significant environmental risk factor for addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Many researchers, including neuroscientists, indicate that the brain disease model presents a misleading, incomplete, and potentially detrimental explanation of addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] In this case, the addictive substance provides brief but total relief and positive feelings of control.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The Adverse Childhood Experiences Study by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has shown a strong dose–response relationship between ACEs and numerous health, social, and behavioral problems throughout a person's lifespan, including substance use disorder.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Children's neurological development can be permanently disrupted when they are chronically exposed to stressful events such as physical, emotional, or sexual abuse, physical or emotional neglect, witnessing violence in the household, or a parent being incarcerated or having a mental illness.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] As a result, the child's cognitive functioning or ability to cope with negative or disruptive emotions may be impaired.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Over time, the child may adopt substance use as a coping mechanism or as a result of reduced impulse control, particularly during adolescence.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Vast amounts of children who experienced abuse have gone on to have some form of addiction in their adolescence or adult life.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] This pathway towards addiction that is opened through stressful experiences during childhood can be avoided by a change in environmental factors throughout an individual's life and opportunities of professional help.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] If one has friends or peers who engage in drug use favorably, the chances of them developing an addiction increases.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Family conflict and home management are causes for one to become engaged in drug use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] According to Travis Hirschi's social control theory, adolescents with stronger attachments to family, religious, academic, and other social institutions are less likely to engage in delinquent and maladaptive behavior, such as drug use leading to addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Adolescence represents a period of increased vulnerability to developing an addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] In adolescence, the incentive-rewards systems in the brain mature well before the cognitive control center.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] This consequently grants the incentive-rewards systems disproportionate power in the behavioral decision-making process.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Therefore, adolescents are increasingly likely to act on their impulses and engage in risky, potentially addictive behavior before considering the consequences.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Not only are adolescents more likely to initiate and maintain drug use, but once addicted they are more resistant to treatment and more liable to relapse.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Most individuals are exposed to and use addictive drugs for the first time during their teenage years.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] In the United States, there were just over 2.8 million new users of illicit drugs in 2013 (7,800 new users per day); among them, 54.1% were under 18 years of age.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] In 2011, there were approximately 20.6 million people in the United States over the age of 12 with an addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Over 90% of those with an addiction began drinking, smoking, or using illicit drugs before the age of 18.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Adolescence is a critical developmental period in which the prefrontal cortex (responsible for planning, inhibitory control, and evaluating long-term consequences) experiences significant maturation.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] During this period, limbic reward circuits mature earlier than prefrontal cortex regulatory networks, creating a developmental imbalance in which reward sensitivity is high, but cognitive control is not fully developed yet.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] This mismatch contributes to higher experimentation with substances and vulnerability to addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Neuroimaging studies show that adolescents exhibit reduced prefrontal cortex activation during decision-making tasks, risk-taking behavior, and heightened dopamine reactivity compared with adults.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Exposure to substances during this early period of their life can disrupt synaptic pruning and myelination.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] This can produce long-term alterations in executive functioning and reward processing that increase the chance of developing a substance use disorder.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Individuals with comorbid (i.e., co-occurring) mental health disorders such as depression, anxiety, attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) or post-traumatic stress disorder are more likely to develop substance use disorders.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The NIDA cites early aggressive behavior as a risk factor for substance use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The National Bureau of Economic Research found that there is a "definite connection between mental illness and the use of addictive substances" and a majority of mental health patients participate in the use of these substances: 38% alcohol, 44% cocaine, and 40% cigarettes.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Epigenetics is the study of stable phenotypic changes that do not involve alterations in the DNA sequence.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Illicit drug use has been found to cause epigenetic changes in DNA methylation, as well as chromatin remodeling.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The epigenetic state of chromatin may pose a risk for the development of substance addictions.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] It has been found that emotional stressors, as well as social adversities, may lead to an initial epigenetic response, which causes an alteration to the reward-signalling pathways.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] This change may predispose one to experience a positive response to drug use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The general classes of epigenetic alterations that have been implicated in transgenerational epigenetic inheritance include DNA methylation, histone modifications, and downregulation or upregulation of microRNAs.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] With respect to addiction, more research is needed to determine the specific heritable epigenetic alterations that arise from various forms of addiction in humans and the corresponding behavioral phenotypes from these epigenetic alterations that occur in human offspring.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Based on preclinical evidence from animal research, certain addiction-induced epigenetic alterations in rats can be transmitted from parent to offspring and produce behavioral phenotypes that decrease the offspring's risk of developing an addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] More generally, the heritable behavioral phenotypes that are derived from addiction-induced epigenetic alterations and transmitted from parent to offspring may serve to either increase or decrease the offspring's risk of developing an addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] DeltaFosB (ΔFosB), a gene transcription factor, is a critical component and common factor in the development of virtually all forms of behavioral and drug addictions.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Two decades of research into ΔFosB's role in addiction have demonstrated that addiction arises, and the associated compulsive behavior intensifies or attenuates, along with the overexpression of ΔFosB in the D1-type medium spiny neurons of the nucleus accumbens.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Chronic addictive drug use causes alterations in gene expression in the mesocorticolimbic projection.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] ΔFosB plays an important role in regulating behavioral responses to natural rewards, such as palatable food, sex, and exercise.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Natural rewards, like drugs of abuse, induce gene expression of ΔFosB in the nucleus accumbens, and chronic acquisition of these rewards can result in a similar pathological addictive state through ΔFosB overexpression.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Consequently, ΔFosB is the key transcription factor involved in addictions to natural rewards (i.e., behavioral addictions) as well; in particular, ΔFosB in the nucleus accumbens is critical for the reinforcing effects of sexual reward.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] This phenomenon is notable since, in humans, a dopamine dysregulation syndrome, characterized by drug-induced compulsive engagement in natural rewards (specifically, sexual activity, shopping, and gambling), has been observed in some individuals taking dopaminergic medications.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] ΔFosB inhibitors (drugs or treatments that oppose its action) may be an effective treatment for addiction and addictive disorders.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The release of dopamine in the nucleus accumbens plays a role in the reinforcing qualities of many forms of stimuli, including naturally reinforcing stimuli like palatable food and sex.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Altered dopamine neurotransmission is frequently observed following the development of an addictive state.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] In humans and lab animals that have developed an addiction, alterations in dopamine or opioid neurotransmission in the nucleus accumbens and other parts of the striatum are evident.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Use of certain drugs (e.g., cocaine) affect cholinergic neurons that innervate the reward system, in turn affecting dopamine signaling in this region.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] A recent study in Addiction reports that GLP-1 agonist medications, such as semaglutide, which are commonly used for diabetes and weight management, may also reduce the risk of overdose and alcohol intoxication in people with substance use disorders.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The study analyzed nearly nine years of health records from 1.3 million individuals across 136 U.S. hospitals, including 500,000 with opioid use disorder and over 800,000 with alcohol use disorder.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Researchers found that those who used Ozempic or similar medications had a 40% lower risk of opioid overdose and a 50% lower risk of alcohol intoxication compared to those not using these drugs.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Understanding the pathways in which drugs act and how drugs can alter those pathways is key when examining the biological basis of drug addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] The reward pathway, known as the mesolimbic pathway, or its extension, the mesocorticolimbic pathway, is characterized by the interaction of several areas of the brain.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Dopamine is the primary neurotransmitter of the reward system in the brain.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] It plays a role in regulating movement, emotion, cognition, motivation, and feelings of pleasure.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Natural rewards, like eating, as well as recreational drug use cause a release of dopamine, and are associated with the reinforcing nature of these stimuli.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Nearly all addictive drugs, directly or indirectly, act on the brain's reward system by heightening dopaminergic activity.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Excessive intake of many types of addictive drugs results in repeated release of high amounts of dopamine, which in turn affects the reward pathway directly through heightened dopamine receptor activation.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Prolonged and abnormally high levels of dopamine in the synaptic cleft can induce receptor downregulation in the neural pathway.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Downregulation of mesolimbic dopamine receptors can result in a decrease in the sensitivity to natural reinforcers.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Drug-seeking behavior is induced by glutamatergic projections from the prefrontal cortex to the nucleus accumbens.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] This idea is supported with data from experiments showing that drug-seeking behavior can be prevented following the inhibition of AMPA glutamate receptors and glutamate release in the nucleus accumbens.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] "Cue-induced wanting" or "cue-triggered wanting", a form of craving that occurs in addiction, is responsible for most of the compulsive behavior that people with addictions exhibit.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] In contrast to ΔFosB's reward-sensitizing effect, CREB transcriptional activity decreases user's sensitivity to the rewarding effects of the substance.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] CREB transcription in the nucleus accumbens is implicated in psychological dependence and symptoms involving a lack of pleasure or motivation during drug withdrawal.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Altered epigenetic regulation of gene expression within the brain's reward system plays a significant and complex role in the development of drug addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] Addictive drugs are associated with three types of epigenetic modifications within neurons.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] These are (1) histone modifications, (2) epigenetic methylation of DNA at CpG sites at (or adjacent to) particular genes, and (3) epigenetic downregulation or upregulation of microRNAs which have particular target genes.
[src:arrack/addiction-p01] As an example, while hundreds of genes in the cells of the nucleus accumbens (NAc) exhibit histone modifications following drug exposure – particularly, altered acetylation and methylation states of histone residues – most other genes in the NAc cells do not show such changes.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The fifth edition of the DSM uses the term *substance use disorder* to refer to a spectrum of drug use-related disorders.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The DSM-5 eliminates the terms *abuse* and *dependence* from diagnostic categories, instead using the specifiers of *mild*, *moderate*, and *severe* to indicate the extent of disordered use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The number of diagnostic criteria present in a given case determines these specifiers.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In the DSM-5, the term *drug addiction* is synonymous with *severe substance use disorder*.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The DSM-5 introduced a new diagnostic category for behavioral addictions.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Problem gambling is the only condition included in this category in the fifth edition.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Internet gaming disorder is listed as a "condition requiring further study" in the DSM-5.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Past editions have used physical dependence and the associated withdrawal syndrome to identify an addictive state.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Physical dependence occurs when the body has adjusted by incorporating the substance into its "normal" functioning – i.e., attains homeostasis – and therefore physical withdrawal symptoms occur on cessation of use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Tolerance is the process by which the body continually adapts to the substance and requires increasingly larger amounts to achieve the original effects.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Withdrawal refers to physical and psychological symptoms experienced when reducing or discontinuing a substance that the body has become dependent on.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Symptoms of withdrawal generally include but are not limited to body aches, anxiety, irritability, intense cravings for the substance, dysphoria, nausea, hallucinations, headaches, cold sweats, tremors, and seizures.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] During acute physical opioid withdrawal, symptoms of restless legs syndrome are common and may be profound.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This phenomenon originated the idiom "kicking the habit".
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Medical researchers who actively study addiction have criticized the DSM classification of addiction for being flawed and involving arbitrary diagnostic criteria.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The eleventh revision of the International Classification of Diseases, commonly referred to as ICD-11, conceptualizes diagnosis somewhat differently.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] ICD-11 first distinguishes between problems with psychoactive substance use ("Disorders due to substance use") and behavioral addictions ("Disorders due to addictive behaviours").
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] With regard to psychoactive substances, ICD-11 explains that the included substances initially produce "pleasant or appealing psychoactive effects that are rewarding and reinforcing with repeated use, [but] with continued use, many of the included substances have the capacity to produce dependence.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The Addictions Neuroclinical Assessment is used to diagnose addiction disorders.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This tool measures three different domains: executive function, incentive salience, and negative emotionality.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Executive functioning consists of processes that would be disrupted in addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In the context of addiction, incentive salience determines how one perceives the addictive substance.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Increased negative emotional responses have been found in individuals with addictions.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This is a screening and assessment tool in one, assessing commonly used substances.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This tool allows for a simple diagnosis, eliminating the need for several screening and assessment tools, as it includes both TAPS-1 and TAPS-2, screening and assessment tools, respectively.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The screening component asks about the frequency of use of the specific substance (tobacco, alcohol, prescription medication, and other).
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] If an individual screens positive, the second component will begin.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This dictates the risk level of the substance.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The CRAFFT (Car-Relax-Alone-Forget-Family and Friends-Trouble) is a screening tool that is used in medical centers.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The CRAFFT is in version 2.1 and has a version for nicotine and tobacco use called the CRAFFT 2.1+N.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This tool is used to identify substance use, substance related driving risk, and addictions among adolescents.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This tool uses a set of questions for different scenarios.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In the case of a specific combination of answers, different question sets can be used to yield a more accurate answer.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] After the questions, the DSM-5 criteria are used to identify the likelihood of the person having substance use disorder.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] After these tests are done, the clinician is to give the "5 RS" of brief counseling.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The Drug Abuse Screening Test (DAST) is a self-reporting tool that measures problematic substance use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Responses to this test are recorded as yes or no answers, and scored as a number between zero and 28.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Drug abuse or dependence is indicated by a cut off score of 6.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Three versions of this screening tool are in use: DAST-28, DAST-20, and DAST-10.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Each of these instruments is copyrighted by Dr.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The Alcohol, Smoking, and Substance Involvement Test (ASSIST) is an interview-based questionnaire consisting of eight questions developed by the WHO.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The questions ask about lifetime use; frequency of use; urge to use; frequency of health, financial, social, or legal problems related to use; failure to perform duties; if anyone has raised concerns over use; attempts to limit or moderate use; and use by injection.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Abuse or addiction liability is the tendency to use drugs in a non-medical situation.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This is typically for euphoria, mood changing, or sedation.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Abuse liability is used when the person using the drugs wants something that they otherwise can not obtain.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The only way to obtain this is through the use of drugs.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] When looking at abuse liability, there are several determining factors in whether the drug is abused.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] These factors are: the chemical makeup of the drug, the effects on the brain, and the age, vulnerability, and health (mental and physical) of the population being studied.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] There are a few drugs with a specific chemical makeup that lead to a high abuse liability.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] These are: cocaine, heroin, inhalants, marijuana, MDMA (ecstasy), methamphetamine, PCP, synthetic cannabinoids, synthetic cathinones (bath salts), nicotine (e.g., tobacco), and alcohol.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Vaccines for addiction have been investigated as a possibility since the early 2000s.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Addictions that have been floated as targets for such treatment include nicotine, opioids, and fentanyl.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Vaccines have been identified as potentially being more effective than other anti-addiction treatments, due to "the long duration of action, the certainty of administration and a potential reduction of toxicity to important organs".
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] As of September 2023, it was further reported that a vaccine "has been tested against heroin and fentanyl and is on its way to being tested against OxyContin".
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The transtheoretical model (TTM) can be used to determine when treatment can begin and which method will be most effective.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] If treatment begins too early, it can cause a person to become defensive and resistant to change.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Due to cultural variations, the proportion of individuals who develop a drug or behavioral addiction within a specified time period (i.e., the prevalence) varies over time, by country, and across national population demographics (e.g., by age group, socioeconomic status, etc.).
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Where addiction is viewed as unacceptable, there will be fewer people addicted.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The prevalence of alcohol dependence is not as high as it is in other regions.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In Asia, not only socioeconomic factors but also biological factors influence drinking behavior.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Internet addiction disorder is highest in the Philippines, according to both the IAT (Internet Addiction Test) – 5% and the CIAS-R (Revised Chen Internet Addiction Scale) – 21%.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The prevalence of substance use disorder among Australians was reported at 5.1% in 2009.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In 2019 the Australian Institute of Health and Welfare conducted a national drug survey that quantified drug use for various types of drugs and demographics.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In 2015, the estimated prevalence among the adult population was 18.4% for heavy episodic alcohol use (in the past 30 days); 15.2% for daily tobacco smoking; and 3.8% for cannabis use, 0.77% for amphetamine use, 0.37% for opioid use, and 0.35% for cocaine use in 2017.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The mortality rates for alcohol and illicit drugs were highest in Eastern Europe.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Data shows a downward trend of alcohol use among children 15 years old in most European countries between 2002 and 2014.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] First-time alcohol use before the age of 13 was recorded for 28% of European children in 2014.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Based on representative samples of the US youth population in 2011, the lifetime prevalence of addictions to alcohol and illicit drugs has been estimated to be approximately 8% and 2–3%, respectively.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Based on representative samples of the US adult population in 2011, the 12-month prevalence of alcohol and illicit drug addictions were estimated at 12% and 2–3% respectively.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The lifetime prevalence of prescription drug addictions is around 4.7%.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] As of 2021, 43.7 million people aged 12 or older surveyed by the National Survey on Drug Use and Health in the United States needed treatment for an addiction to alcohol, nicotine, or other drugs.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The groups with the highest number of people were 18–25 years (25.1%) and "American Indian or Alaska Native" (28.7%).
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Only about 10%, or a little over 2 million, receive any form of treatments, and those that do generally do not receive evidence-based care.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] One-third of inpatient hospital costs and 20% of all deaths in the US every year are the result of untreated addictions and risky substance use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Despite the massive overall economic cost to society, which is greater than the cost of diabetes and all forms of cancer combined, most doctors in the US lack the training to address a drug addiction effectively.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Estimates of lifetime prevalence rates in the US are 1–2% for compulsive gambling, 5% for sexual addiction, 2.8% for food addiction, and 5–6% for compulsive shopping.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The time-invariant prevalence rate for sexual addiction and related compulsive sexual behavior (e.g., compulsive masturbation with or without pornography, compulsive cybersex, etc.) within the US ranges from 3–6% of the population.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] According to a 2017 poll conducted by the Pew Research Center, almost half of US adults know a family member or close friend who has struggled with a drug addiction at some point in their life.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In 2019, opioid addiction was acknowledged as a national crisis in the United States.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The National Epidemiologic Survey on Alcohol and Related Conditions found that from 2012 to 2013, the prevalence of Cannabis use disorder in U.S. adults was 2.9%.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] A Statistics Canada Survey in 2012 found the lifetime prevalence and 12-month prevalence of substance use disorders were 21.6% and 4.4% in those 15 and older.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Alcohol abuse or dependence reported a lifetime prevalence of 18.1% and a 12-month prevalence of 3.2%.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Cannabis abuse or dependence reported a lifetime prevalence of 6.8% and a 12-month prevalence of 3.2%.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Other drug abuse or dependence has a lifetime prevalence of 4.0% and a 12-month prevalence of 0.7%.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] *Substance use disorder* is a term used interchangeably with *a drug addiction*.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In Ontario, Canada between 2009 and 2017, outpatient visits for mental health and addiction increased from 52.6 to 57.2 per 100 people, emergency department visits increased from 13.5 to 19.7 per 1000 people, and the number of hospitalizations increased from 4.5 to 5.5 per 1000 people.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Prevalence of care needed increased the most among the 14–17 age group overall.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The realities of opioid use and opioid use disorder in Latin America may be deceptive if observations are limited to epidemiological findings.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime report, although South America produced 3% of the world's morphine and heroin and 0.01% of its opium, prevalence of use is uneven.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] According to the Inter-American Commission on Drug Abuse Control, consumption of heroin is low in most Latin American countries, although Colombia is the area's largest opium producer.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Mexico, because of its border with the United States, has the highest incidence of use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The word *addiction* derives from the Latin "*addico*", meaning "giving over" with both positive connotations (devotion, dedication) and negative ones (being enslaved to a creditor in Roman law).
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This dual meaning persisted in traditional English dictionaries, encompassing both legal surrender and personal devotion to habits.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Later, the 19th century temperance movements narrowed the definition of addiction to just drug-related disease, ignoring behavioral addictions and the possibility of positive or neutral addictions.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This restrictive view opposes the current understanding of addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The etymology of the term *addiction* throughout history has been misunderstood and has taken on various meanings associated with the word.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] An example is the usage of the word in the religious landscape of early modern Europe.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] "Addiction" at the time meant "to attach" to something, giving it both positive and negative connotations.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The object of this attachment could be characterized as "good or bad".
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The meaning of addiction during the early modern period was mostly associated with positivity and goodness; during this early modern and highly religious era of Christian revivalism and Pietistic tendencies, it was seen as a way of "devoting oneself to another".
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In contemporary English, "-holic" is a suffix that can be added to a subject to denote an addiction to it.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] It was extracted from the word alcoholism (one of the first addictions to be widely identified both medically and socially) (correctly the root "alcohol" plus the suffix "-ism") by misdividing or rebracketing it into "alco" and "-holism".
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Modern research on addiction has led to a better understanding of the disease with research on the topic dating back to 1875, specifically on morphine addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This furthered the understanding of addiction being a medical condition.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] It was not until the 19th century that addiction was seen and acknowledged in the Western world as a disease, being both a physical condition and mental illness.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Today, addiction is understood both as a biopsychosocial and neurological disorder that negatively impacts those who are affected by it, most commonly associated with the use of drugs and excessive use of alcohol.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The understanding of addiction has changed throughout history, which has impacted and continues to impact the ways it is medically treated and diagnosed.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The arts can be used in a variety of ways to address issues related to addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Art can be used as a form of therapy in the treatment of substance use disorders.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Creative activities like painting, sculpting, music, and writing can help people express their feelings and experiences in safe and healthy ways.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The arts can be used as an assessment tool to identify underlying issues that may be contributing to a person's substance use disorder.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Through art, individuals can gain insights into their own motivations and behaviors that can help determine a course of treatment.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Finally, the arts can be used to advocate for those suffering from a substance use disorder by raising awareness of the issue and promoting understanding and compassion.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Through art, individuals can share their stories, increase awareness, and offer support and hope to those struggling with substance use disorders.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Addiction treatment is complex and not always effective due to engagement and service availability concerns, so researchers prioritize efforts to improve treatment retention and decrease relapse rates.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Characteristics of substance abuse may include feelings of isolation, a lack of confidence, communication difficulties, and a perceived lack of control.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In a similar vein, people suffering from substance use disorders tend to be highly sensitive, creative, and as such, are likely able to express themselves meaningfully in creative arts such as dancing, painting, writing, music, and acting.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Further evidenced by Waller and Mahony (2002) and Kaufman (1981), the creative arts therapies can be a suitable treatment option for this population especially when verbal communication is ineffective.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Art therapy is an effective method of dealing with substance abuse in comprehensive treatment models.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] When included in psychoeducational programs, art therapy in a group setting can help clients internalize taught concepts in a more personalized manner.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] During the course of treatment, by examining and comparing artwork created at different times, art therapists can help identify and diagnose issues, as well as charting the extent or direction of improvement as a person detoxifies.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Art therapy can function as a complementary therapy used in conjunction with more conventional therapies and can integrate with harm reduction protocols to minimize the negative effects of drug use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] An evaluation of art therapy incorporation within a pre-existing Addiction Treatment Programme based on the 12 step Minnesota Model endorsed by the Alcoholics Anonymous found that 66% of participants expressed the usefulness of art therapy as a part of treatment.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Within the weekly art therapy session, clients were able to reflect and process the intense emotions and cognitions evoked by the programme.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In turn, the art therapy component of the programme fostered stronger self-awareness, exploration, and externalization of repressed and unconscious emotions of clients, promoting the development of a more integrated 'authentic self'.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Music therapy was identified to have potentially strong beneficial effects in aiding contemplation and preparing those diagnosed with substance use for treatment.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The Formal Elements Art Therapy Scale (FEATS) is an assessment tool used to evaluate drawings created by people suffering from substance use disorders by comparing them to drawings of a control group (consisting of individuals without SUDs).
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] FEATS consists of twelve elements, three of which were found to be particularly effective at distinguishing the drawings of those with SUDs from those without: Person, Realism, and Developmental.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] By using the FEATS assessment tool, clinicians can gain valuable insight into the drawings of individuals with SUDs, and can compare them to those of the control group.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Formal assessments such as FEATS provide healthcare providers with a means to quantify, standardize, and communicate abstract and visceral characteristics of SUDs to provide more accurate diagnoses and informed treatment decisions.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Other artistic assessment methods include the Bird's Nest Drawing: a useful tool for visualizing a client's attachment security.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This assessment method looks at the amount of color used in the drawing, with a lack of color indicating an 'insecure attachment', a factor that the client's therapist or recovery framework must take into account.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Art therapists working with children of parents suffering from alcoholism can use the Kinetic Family Drawings assessment tool to shed light on family dynamics and help children express and understand their family experiences.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The KFD can be used in family sessions to allow children to share their experiences and needs with parents who may be in recovery from alcohol use disorder.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Depiction of isolation of self and isolation of other family members may be an indicator of parental alcoholism.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Stigma can lead to feelings of shame that can prevent people with substance use disorders from seeking help and interfere with the provision of harm reduction services.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] It can influence healthcare policy, making it difficult for these individuals to access treatment.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Artists attempt to change the societal perception of addiction from a punishable moral offense to a chronic illness necessitating treatment.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This form of advocacy can help to relocate the fight of addiction from a judicial perspective to the public health system.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Artists who have personally lived with addiction or undergone recovery may use art to depict their experiences in a manner that uncovers the "human face of addiction".
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] By bringing experiences of addiction and recovery to a personal level and breaking down the "us and them", the viewer may be more inclined to show compassion, forego stereotypes and stigma of addiction, and label addiction as a social rather than individual problem.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The Temple University College of Public Health department conducted a project to raise awareness of opioid use and reduce associated stigma by asking students to create art pieces that were displayed on a website they created and promoted via social media.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Quantitative and qualitative data were recorded to measure engagement, and the student artists were interviewed, which revealed a change in perspective and understanding, as well as greater appreciation of diverse experiences.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Ultimately, the project found that art was an effective medium for empowering both the artist creating the work and the person interacting with it.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] A project known as "Voice" was a collection of art, poetry, and narratives created by women living with a history of addiction to explore women's understanding of harm reduction, challenge the effects of stigma, and give voice to those who have historically been silenced or devalued.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In the project, nurses with knowledge of mainstream systems, aesthetic knowing, feminism, and substance use organized weekly gatherings, wherein women with histories of substance use and addiction worked alongside a nurse to create artistic expressions.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Creations were presented at several venues, including an International Conference on Drug Related Harm, a Nursing Conference, and a local gallery, to a positive response.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] While regarded biomedically as a neuropsychological disorder, addiction is multi-layered, with biological, psychological, social, cultural, and spiritual (biopsychosocial–cultural–spiritual) elements.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] A biopsychosocial–cultural–spiritual approach fosters the crossing of disciplinary boundaries, and promotes holistic considerations of addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] A biopsychosocial–cultural–spiritual approach considers, for example, how physical environments influence experiences, habits, and patterns of addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Some biological influences of the biopsychosocial model include genetic heritability, neuroadaptations in reward circuitry, and changes in neurotransmitter systems.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Some examples of neurotransmitters that are affected include: dopamine, GABA, and glutamate.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Twin and family studies show that heritability accounts for approximately 40-60% of the variance that we see in addiction risk.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Chronic substance exposure seems to produce long-term changes in the mesolimbic dopamine system.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This includes altered activity in the ventral tegmental area and nucleus accumbens, which contribute to things like incentive salience, craving, and compulsive drug-seeking behavior.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] These biological factors contribute to things like the initial vulnerability and the development of drug-seeking behaviors.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] It does this by altering factors like reward sensitivity, stress reactivity, and executive control systems.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] These adaptations, specifically those impacting the dopaminergic responsivity and prefrontal regulation, interact with psychological traits and social experiences.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Examples are interacting with impulsivity, coping style, or chronic stress exposure.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Together, these interactions increase the motivational value of drug cues.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] It also increases the chance that dopaminergic activity will drive compulsive use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This makes biology just one component of a broader system that shapes addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This includes learning processes, impulsivity, reward sensitivity, and the use of substances as coping mechanisms for negative affect or trauma.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Conditioning based models show that environmental cues can acquire motivational significance and potentially trigger craving and relapse, even after periods of long abstinence.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Psychological factors primarily shape how people perceive, react to, and regulate internal states.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This shows how these factors influence the use of substances as coping strategies or sources of reinforcement.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] These processes interact with vulnerabilities in both biological and social contexts by making each one strengthen the other.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Biological sensitivities make a person more strongly react to social challenges.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] These social challenges repeatedly activate and increase biological sensitivity.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] A cycle is created where both types of vulnerabilities keep reinforcing each other.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] These include: impaired inhibitory control, heightened reward drive, stress, and trauma.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] These interactions determine whether substance use will evolve into damaging patterns (compulsive drug seeking behaviors, loss of control of drug use, reliance on substance for coping) that are characteristic of addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Social and environmental influences include family dynamics, early and adverse experiences, socioeconomic status, peer networks, and cultural norms.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Longitudinal studies show that adverse childhood experiences can significantly increase the chance of substance use later in life.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This is mainly due to the interaction with neurodevelopmental stress pathways.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Together, these levels of analysis highlight addiction as a complex and dynamic condition emerging from the interaction of several aspects including: neurobiological processes, individual psychological traits, and broader social environments.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This model is widely used in contemporary clinical practice and public health because it accounts for a lot of variability in addiction trajectories, relapse patterns, and treatment outcomes across several individuals.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Social factors exhibit their greatest influence on things like exposure to substances, motivation, and the probability of a potential escalation or relapse.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Social factors act through mechanisms like chronic stress, peer modeling, socioeconomic constraints, and the availability of substances.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Social factors act through mediums like chronic stress, which dysregulates the HPA axis and sensitizes neural circuits involved in threat detection.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Substance availability can increase the chance of repeated exposure and reinforcement.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This will strengthen habit circuits and lower the threshold for dependence on the substance.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Environmental pressures interact with biological predispositions and psychological coping mechanisms to show that addictive behavior will emerge from the combined effects of social context, brain function, and individual psychological processes.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The cultural model, an anthropological understanding of the emergence of drug use and abuse, was developed by Dwight Heath.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Heath undertook ethnographic research and fieldwork with the Camba people of Bolivia from June 1956 to August 1957.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Heath observed that adult members of society drank 'large quantities of rum and became intoxicated for several contiguous days at least twice a month'.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] This frequent, heavy drinking from which intoxication followed was typically undertaken socially, during festivals.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Having returned in 1989, Heath observed that while much had changed, 'drinking parties' remained, as per his initial observations, and 'there appear to be no harmful consequences to anyone'.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Heath's observations and interactions reflected that this form of social behavior, the habitual heavy consumption of alcohol, was encouraged and valued, enforcing social bonds in the Camba community.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Despite frequent intoxication, "even to the point of unconsciousness", the Camba held no concept of alcoholism (a form of addiction), and no visible social problems associated with drunkenness, or addiction, were apparent.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] As noted by Merrill Singer, Heath's findings, when considered alongside subsequent cross-cultural experiences, challenged the perception that intoxication is socially 'inherently disruptive'.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Following this fieldwork, Heath proposed the 'cultural model', suggesting that 'problems' associated with heavy drinking, such as alcoholism – a recognised form of addiction – were cultural: that is, that alcoholism is determined by cultural beliefs, and therefore varies among cultures.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Heath's findings challenged the notion that 'continued use [of alcohol] is inexorably addictive and damaging to the consumer's health'.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The cultural model did face criticism by Sociologist Robin Room and others, who felt anthropologists could "downgrade the severity of the problem".
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Historically, addiction has been viewed from the etic perspective, defining users through the pathology of their condition.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] As reports of drug use rapidly increased, the cultural model found application in anthropological research exploring western drug subculture practices.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The approach evolved from the ethnographic exploration into the lived experiences and subjectivities of 1960s and 70s drug subcultures.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The seminal publication "Taking care of business", by Edward Preble and John J.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Casey, documented the daily lives of New York street-based intravenous heroin users in detail, providing insight into the dynamic social worlds and activities that surrounded their drug use.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] These findings challenge popular narratives of immorality and deviance, conceptualizing substance abuse as a social phenomenon.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The prevailing culture can influence drug-taking behaviors, along with the physical and psychological effects of the drug.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] To marginalized individuals, drug subcultures can provide social connection, symbolic meaning, and socially constructed purpose that they may feel is unattainable through conventional means.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The subcultural model demonstrates the complexities of addiction, highlighting the need for an integrated approach.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] It contends that a biosocial approach is required to achieve a holistic understanding of addiction.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Emerging in the early 1980s, the critical medical anthropology model was introduced, and as Merrill Singer offers 'was applied quickly to the analysis of drug use'.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] These three key points highlight how drugs may come to be used to self-medicate the psychological trauma of socio-political disparity and injustice, intertwining with licit and illicit drug market politics.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Social suffering, "the misery among those on the weaker end of power relations in terms of physical health, mental health and lived experience", is used by anthropologists to analyze how individuals may have personal problems caused by political and economic power.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] From the perspective of critical medical anthropology, heavy drug use and addiction are consequences of such larger-scale unequal distributions of power.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The three models developed here – the cultural model, the subcultural model, and the Critical Medical Anthropology Model – display how addiction is not an experience to be considered only biomedically.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Through consideration of addiction alongside the biological, psychological, social, cultural, and spiritual (biopsychosocial–spiritual) elements which influence its experience, a holistic and comprehensive understanding can be built.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Albert Bandura's 1977 social learning theory posits that individuals acquire addictive behaviors by observing and imitating models in their social environment.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The likelihood of engaging in and sustaining similar addictive behaviors is influenced by the reinforcement and punishment observed in others.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The principle of reciprocal determinism suggests that the functional relationships between personal, environmental, and behavioral factors act as determinants of addictive behavior.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Thus, effective treatment targets each dynamic facet of the biopsychosocial disorder.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The transtheoretical model of change suggests that overcoming an addiction is a stepwise process that occurs through several stages.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The transtheoretical model can help guide the development of tailored behavioral interventions that can promote lasting change.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Progression through these stages may not always follow a linear path, as individuals may move back and forth between stages.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Resistance to change is recognized as an expected part of the process.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] Addiction causes an "astoundingly high financial and human toll" on individuals and society as a whole.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] In the United States, the total economic cost to society is greater than that of all types of diabetes and all cancers combined.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] The US National Institute on Drug Abuse has found that overdose deaths in the US have almost tripled among males and females from 2002 to 2017, with 72,306 overdose deaths reported in 2017 in the US.
[src:arrack/addiction-p02] 2020 marked the year with the highest number of overdose deaths over a 12-month period, with 81,000 overdose deaths, exceeding the records set in 2017.
[src:arrack/arrack] There are two primary styles of arrack that are very different from one another: *Batavia arrack* is often clear in color but has a flavor profile more similar to dark rum, with a distinctive "funk" or "hogo" imparted to it from fermented red rice.
[src:arrack/arrack] Sri Lankan (Ceylon) arrack, by contrast, is a more refined and subtle spirit.
[src:arrack/arrack] It has hints of cognac and rum character and a wealth of delicate floral notes.
[src:arrack/arrack] Both styles are also made "in house" by local citizenry and can be more akin to moonshine in their presentation.
[src:arrack/arrack] The word derived from the Arabic word *arak* (عرق, *ʿaraq*), meaning 'distillate'.
[src:arrack/arrack] In the Eastern Mediterranean, the term *arak* is usually used for liquor distilled from grapes and flavored with anise.
[src:arrack/arrack] The word "arrack" has been considered by some experts to be derived from *areca nut*, a palm seed originating in India from the areca tree and used as the basis for many varieties of arrack.
[src:arrack/arrack] In 1838, Samuel Morewood's work on the histories of liquors was published.
[src:arrack/arrack] He notes several examples of the word and its derivatives among other ethnic groups: the Tungusians, Calmucks, and Kirghizes use the terms "arrack" or "rak", and the Ossetians "applied the word 'Arak' to denote all distilled liquors".
[src:arrack/arrack] Strabo reports Indians made a beverage from rice known as arak.
[src:arrack/arrack] Arrack predates all "New World" spirits, as it is a parent to cachaça (which was, in turn, the parent of rum, rhum agricole, and ron).
[src:arrack/arrack] Genoese merchants made the spirit as a byproduct of their sugar cane production in the Canary Islands.
[src:arrack/arrack] In addition to making sugar, they produced arrack instead of importing it for their growing list of customers.
[src:arrack/arrack] Other early arrack was distilled from molasses and water, using dried cakes of red rice and botanicals that contained yeast and other fungi to trigger the fermentation process (this technique can be traced back thousands of years to China and even predates the birth of distillation).
[src:arrack/arrack] It is also claimed to have been distilled in India in 800 BCE, but while palm wine and fermented sugarcane drinks were being made around this time, not all believe that formal distillation was taking place.
[src:arrack/arrack] Outside Asia, the spirit was a common ingredient in the proliferation of Indian alcoholic punch, and was particularly popular in Holland and Sweden.
[src:arrack/arrack] It was the first distilled spirit consumed in colonial America, in the colonies of New Sweden and New Netherland, but is now mostly confused with the more common and similar spelled anise-flavored spirit arak.
[src:arrack/arrack] Regardless of the exact origin, arrack has come to symbolize a multitude of largely unrelated, distilled alcohols produced throughout Asia and the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:arrack/arrack] This is largely due to the proliferation of distillation knowledge throughout the Middle East during the 14th century.
[src:arrack/arrack] Each country named its own alcohol by using various Latin alphabet forms of the same word that was synonymous with distillation at the time (*arak, araka, araki, ariki, arrack, arack, raki, raque, racque, rac, rak*).
[src:arrack/arrack] 1864 English and Australian Cookery Book described arrack as "a spirituous liquor from the East Indies.
[src:arrack/arrack] This term, or its corruption, rack, is applied to any spirituous liquor in the East.
[src:arrack/arrack] The true arrack is said to be distilled from *toddy*, the fermented juice of the coconut flower.
[src:arrack/arrack] Arrack was banned in the states of Kerala in 1996, and Karnataka on 1 July 2007.
[src:arrack/arrack] Within Indonesia itself, the term *arak* is still widely used to describe arrack.
[src:arrack/arrack] Arak (or rice wine) was a popular alcoholic beverage during the colonial era.
[src:arrack/arrack] It is considered the "rum" of Indonesia because, like rum, it is distilled from sugarcane.
[src:arrack/arrack] To start the fermentation, local fermented red rice is combined with local yeast to give a unique flavor and smell of the distillate.
[src:arrack/arrack] It is distilled to approximately 70% ABV.
[src:arrack/arrack] Like rum, Batavia-arrack is often a blend of different original parcels.
[src:arrack/arrack] One of the longest established arrack companies in Indonesia is the Batavia Arak Company (Dutch *Batavia-Arak Maatschappij*), which was already in business by 1872, became a limited liability company in 1901, and was still operating in the early 1950s.
[src:arrack/arrack] The Batavia Arak Company also exported arrack to the Netherlands and had an office in Amsterdam.
[src:arrack/arrack] Some of the arrack brands produced by Batavia Arak Company were KWT (produced in the Bandengan [Kampung Baru] area of old Jakarta) and OGL.
[src:arrack/arrack] Still commonly available in Northern Europe and Southern Asia, Batavia-arrack can be difficult to find in the United States.
[src:arrack/arrack] *Batavia-Arrack van Oosten* is a more recently available brand.
[src:arrack/arrack] Batavia-arrack is said to enhance flavor when used as a component in other products, such as pastries (like the Finnish Runeberg torte or the Dresdner Stollen), or in the confectionery and flavor industries.
[src:arrack/arrack] It is used in herbal and bitter liqueurs, and as a component in alcoholic punches (such as punsch, regent punch, royal punch, and black tea-port milk punch).
[src:arrack/arrack] Its use in punch was noted by early American bartender Jerry Thomas: "Most of the arrack imported into this country is distilled from rice, and comes from Batavia.
[src:arrack/arrack] It is but little used in America, except to flavor punch; the taste of it is very agreeable in this mixture.
[src:arrack/arrack] It is much used in some parts of India, where it is distilled from toddy, the juice of the coconut tree".
[src:arrack/arrack] In Indonesia, arrack is often created as a form of moonshine.
[src:arrack/arrack] Indonesian arrack containing methanol has caused both local and tourist deaths from methanol toxicity.
[src:arrack/arrack] Arrack plays a socially and culturally important role in Balinese society, where it is often diluted with water, shared with friends, or drunk in small quantities during religious ceremonies.
[src:arrack/arrack] However, with the growth of tourism, the need for cheap alcohol, and increases in alcohol import taxes and regulations, arrack became the spirit of choice for many mixed drinks in bars.
[src:arrack/arrack] With the growth in arrack production and popularity, more deaths from methanol poisoning were reported.
[src:arrack/arrack] Arrack is usually sold on the black market, without regulation, where methanol is sometimes added for economic reasons, or out of the assumption that it will be more potent.
[src:arrack/arrack] A Filipino term for distilled and undistilled alcoholic drinks in general is *alak*, derived from the Arabic word *ʿaraq*.
[src:arrack/arrack] The term *arak*, though, is specifically used in Ilocano.
[src:arrack/arrack] It can be derived from palm sap (notably coconut, nipa palm, or kaong palm), sugarcane, or rice.
[src:arrack/arrack] Traditionally distilled native alcohols include lambanóg and laksoy, which are made from the sap of palm flowers.
[src:arrack/arrack] The sap is harvested into bamboo receptacles similar to rubber tapping, then cooked or fermented to produce a mildly-alcoholic coconut toddy called *tubâ*.
[src:arrack/arrack] The *tubâ*, which by itself is also a popular beverage, is further distilled to produce lambanóg (or laksoy, if made from nipa palm sap).
[src:arrack/arrack] The Italian explorer Antonio Pigafetta stated that the arrack that he drank in Palawan and nearby islands in 1521 was made from distilled rice wine.
[src:arrack/arrack] However, he was likely referring to *pangasi*, an undistilled rice wine.
[src:arrack/arrack] Sri Lanka is the largest producer of coconut arrack and, until 1992, the government played a significant role in its production.
[src:arrack/arrack] Other than water, the entire manufacturing process revolves around the fermentation and distillation of a single ingredient, the sap of unopened flowers from a coconut palm (*Cocos nucifera*).
[src:arrack/arrack] Each morning at dawn, men known as toddy tappers move among the tops of coconut trees using connecting ropes not unlike tightropes.
[src:arrack/arrack] A single tree may contribute up to two litres per day.
[src:arrack/arrack] Due to its concentrated sugar and yeast content, the captured liquid naturally and immediately ferments into a mildly alcoholic drink called "toddy", *tuak*, or occasionally "palm wine".
[src:arrack/arrack] Within a few hours after collection, the toddy is poured into large wooden vats, called "washbacks", made from the wood of teak or Berrya cordifolia.
[src:arrack/arrack] The natural fermentation process is allowed to continue in the washbacks until the alcohol content reaches 5–7% and deemed ready for distillation.
[src:arrack/arrack] Distillation is generally a two-step process involving either pot stills, continuous stills, or a combination of both.
[src:arrack/arrack] The first step results in "low wine", a liquid with an alcohol content between 20 and 40%.
[src:arrack/arrack] The second step results in the final distillate with an alcohol content of 60 to 90%.
[src:arrack/arrack] It is generally diluted to between 33% and 50% alcohol by volume (ABV) or 66 to 100 proof.
[src:arrack/arrack] The entire distillation process is completed within 24 hours.
[src:arrack/arrack] Various blends of coconut arrack diverge in processing, yet the extracted spirit may also be sold raw, repeatedly distilled or filtered, or transferred back into halmilla vats for maturing up to 15 years, depending on flavour, colour and fragrance requirements.
[src:arrack/arrack] Premium blends of arrack add no other ingredients, while the inexpensive and common blends are mixed with neutral spirits before bottling.
[src:arrack/arrack] Most people describe the taste as resembling "... a blend between whiskey and rum", similar, but distinctively different at the same time.
[src:arrack/arrack] Coconut arrack is traditionally consumed by itself or with ginger beer, a popular soda in Sri Lanka.
[src:arrack/arrack] It also may be mixed in cocktails as a substitute for the required portions of either rum or whiskey.
[src:arrack/arrack] Arrack is often combined with popular mixers such as cola, soda water, and lime juice.
[src:arrack/arrack] Ceylon Arrack, a brand of Sri Lankan coconut arrack, was recently launched in the UK in 2010.
[src:arrack/arrack] It is also available in France and Germany.
[src:arrack/arrack] White Lion VSOA entered the American market soon after.
[src:arrack/arrack] Historically arrack has been a common beverage on the island of Saint Helena, distilled from potatoes.
[src:arrack/arrack] This is likely due to influences of the East India Company, which controlled Saint Helena and used it as a halfway point between India and England.
[src:arrack/arrack] In Sweden and Finland, Batavia-arrack has historically been mixed with other ingredients in order to make Swedish punsch (now available in prepackaged bottles).
[src:arrack/arrack] The alcohol content is normally not over 25%, although it has a high sugar content of nearly 30%.
[src:arrack/arrack] The original recipe was a mixture of arrack with water, sugar, lemon, and tea or spices (chiefly nutmeg).
[src:arrack/arrack] Today punsch is drunk warm (in Sweden) or cold (in Finland) as an accompaniment to yellow split pea soup (in Sweden) or green split pea soup (in Finland), or chilled as an after dinner drink accompanied with coffee (especially during dinner parties at student nations).
[src:arrack/arrack] It is used as a flavouring in several types of pastries and sweets as well.
[src:arrack/arrack] The name arrack is still retained for some pastries, for example *arraksboll*, whereas punsch is used for things like *punschrulle*.
[src:arrack/arrack] In Finland, arrack (or rum) usually serves as one of the ingredients in the making one of the Finnish traditional pastries, Runeberg tortes.
